<h1>Designing a Privacy-Conscious Back-in-Stock Notification MVP for Shopify</h1>

<p><strong>First-draft status:</strong> This is a student review draft. Before submitting it, replace the reflection prompts with your own words, verify all prototype details against your code and evidence, and confirm any Canvas-specific word-count requirement.</p>

<p>When a customer visits an online store and finds a desired product out of stock, the merchant often loses the sale. This project investigates a specific solution: a back-in-stock notification workflow. The goal is to capture a customer's email request, process a simulated inventory event, and handle the data safely without sending duplicate emails.</p>

<p>The prototype demonstrated the core event-processing path using invented data. However, the development-only email connection could not be verified locally, so email capture remains a documented limitation rather than a claimed outcome. This article explains the problem, the technical design, the ethical considerations, and the lessons learned during development.</p>

<h2>1. The Problem: Losing Customers to Stockouts</h2>

<p>Stockouts are a common problem in e-commerce. When a product is unavailable, customers may leave the store and buy from a competitor. Dadzie and Winston (2007)<a href="#ref-1">[1]</a> found that stockouts can negatively affect a customer's assessment of an online transaction and their intention to buy again. Kim, Knight and Mitrofanov (2024)<a href="#ref-2">[2]</a> also identify stockouts as a significant risk to customer loyalty.</p>

<p>To address this, merchants need a way to tell customers when a product is available again. This project created a Minimum Viable Product (MVP) prototype. It uses a Shopify development store, a Node.js server, and a MongoDB database. It uses invented data and a controlled test event to simulate a restock, focusing on the core logic rather than building a full commercial app.</p>

<h2>2. Industry Trend: Event-Driven Architecture</h2>

<p>Modern e-commerce applications often use an event-driven design. Instead of constantly asking the store "is the product available yet?" (polling), the store sends a message (an event) only when the inventory changes. Shopify (n.d.)<a href="#ref-3">[3]</a> supports this through webhooks, which are near-real-time notifications that trigger actions in an application.</p>

<p>Existing Shopify App Store listings from Notify Me! (n.d.)<a href="#ref-4">[4]</a>, Swym Corporation (n.d.)<a href="#ref-5">[5]</a>, and Appikon Software Pvt Ltd (n.d.)<a href="#ref-6">[6]</a> show that commercial back-in-stock products already exist. These commercial apps offer many features like SMS alerts, analytics, and theme customization. This student project does not try to compete with them. Instead, it deliberately reduces the scope to study how the core event and data workflow operates.</p>

<h2>3. Technical Issues and Design Choices</h2>

The ERD includes fields related to email delivery, such as emailMessageId and sentAt. These features were intentionally excluded from the prototype implementation. The purpose of the project was to validate the data model, notification registration workflow, and inventory-event matching process. Email delivery introduces additional complexity, including SMTP configuration, retry policies, bounce handling, and security considerations. Future work could integrate SendGrid, AWS SES, or another email provider to deliver real notifications after a matching inventory event is detected.

<p>Building a reliable notification system requires solving several technical problems:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Event Duplication:</strong> Webhooks can sometimes be delivered more than once. The design must prevent a repeated delivery from repeating a state-changing action. The controlled event-processing path saves a <code>ProcessedInventoryEvent</code> with a unique delivery ID. Testing showed that a duplicate event was correctly recognized and did not cause a second request transition. This does not prove duplicate email delivery prevention because successful SMTP delivery was not demonstrated.</li>
    <li><strong>Input Validation:</strong> The system must reject bad data. Controlled tests confirmed that invalid inventory values or unsupported fields returned an HTTP 400 error.</li>
    <li><strong>Exact Matching:</strong> An inventory event must only consider requests for the exact product variant that was restocked. The controlled processing logic matches requests using the store domain, the specific inventory item ID, and a <code>pending</code> status.</li>
    <li><strong>Event Reliability:</strong> Shopify (n.d.)<a href="#ref-3">[3]</a> warns that webhook delivery is not guaranteed. Because live webhook proof was outside the completed evidence, this prototype used a controlled test fixture to simulate the event reliably.</li>
    <li><strong>Test-Email Transport:</strong> A test system should never send emails to real people. Nodemailer (n.d.)<a href="#ref-7">[7]</a> documents Ethereal test accounts, so Nodemailer with Ethereal was chosen. However, local SMTP verification failed, which is discussed later as a limitation.</li>
</ul>

<h2>4. Ethical and Privacy Considerations</h2>

<p>A notification system handles personal data (email addresses), so it must be designed ethically.</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Data Minimization:</strong> The MVP data model is limited to the email address needed for a one-time notification, plus product references and operational timestamps. It does not require a phone number, date of birth, or payment details. This design aligns with the Australian Privacy Principles (APP 3), for which the Office of the Australian Information Commissioner (2026)<a href="#ref-8">[8]</a> states that collection must be reasonably necessary.</li>
    <li><strong>Purpose and Transparency:</strong> The form must clearly state that the email is only for a one-time notification. It should not automatically subscribe the user to general marketing, consistent with the Office of the Australian Information Commissioner (2019)<a href="#ref-9">[9]</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Security:</strong> Secrets (like database passwords) must be kept out of the code repository. They are loaded using environment variables.</li>
    <li><strong>Accessibility:</strong> The MVP requirements specify clear labels, understandable errors, keyboard operation, visible focus, and text-based status feedback. These are design requirements informed by World Wide Web Consortium guidance (n.d.)<a href="#ref-11">[11]</a>. Full accessibility conformance is not claimed because a formal audit has not yet been completed.</li>
</ul>

<h2>5. The Data Model</h2>

<p>The system needs to remember two main things: the customer's request and the restock event. This is modeled in MongoDB using two collections:</p>

<table border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0">
    <tr>
        <th>Entity</th>
        <th>Business Fact</th>
        <th>Key Attributes</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><code>NotificationRequest</code></td>
        <td>A customer wants to know when a specific variant is available.</td>
        <td><code>_id</code>, <code>emailNormalized</code>, <code>shopDomain</code>, <code>variantId</code>, <code>status</code> (e.g., pending, processing, sent).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><code>ProcessedInventoryEvent</code></td>
        <td>A restock event was received and must be remembered to prevent duplicates.</td>
        <td><code>_id</code>, <code>deliveryId</code>, <code>inventoryItemId</code>, <code>available</code> quantity.</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<p>MongoDB (n.d.)<a href="#ref-12">[12]</a> uses documents, where <code>_id</code> is the primary key. MongoDB (n.d.)<a href="#ref-13">[13]</a> supports unique indexes to enforce rules, such as ensuring that the <code>deliveryId</code> is unique. The application logic connects the two entities by matching the inventory item ID.</p>

<h2>6. Technology Selection</h2>

<p>The project uses a small JavaScript/Node.js/MongoDB architecture. React was considered but deliberately excluded from this MVP to keep the storefront scope small. Therefore, it would not be accurate to describe the implemented prototype as a full MERN application.</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Server:</strong> The OpenJS Foundation (n.d.)<a href="#ref-14">[14]</a> describes Node.js as an asynchronous, event-driven environment. Express.js (n.d.)<a href="#ref-16">[16]</a> provides routing and middleware. Python with Flask is a reasonable alternative, as documented by Pallets Projects (n.d.)<a href="#ref-15">[15]</a>, but Node was chosen to align with existing JavaScript skills.</li>
    <li><strong>Database:</strong> MongoDB suits the distinct document structures of requests and events. PostgreSQL is an alternative that provides explicit relational constraints, as documented by PostgreSQL Global Development Group (n.d.)<a href="#ref-17">[17]</a>, but MongoDB was selected based on prior experience.</li>
    <li><strong>Store Integration:</strong> A Shopify development store was selected to support safe testing without affecting real customers, as Shopify (n.d.)<a href="#ref-18">[18]</a> describes.</li>
</ul>

