<h2>8. Limitations: What Was Attempted</h2>

<p>The controlled prototype evidence demonstrates event persistence, request matching, input validation, and duplicate-event handling. However, the email delivery part reached an attempted resolution rather than a complete one.</p>

<p>The test email component generated a valid Ethereal configuration consistent with Nodemailer guidance (n.d.)<a href="#ref-7">[7]</a>. However, transport verification failed at a local Node.js socket connection stage (<code>ESOCKET</code> / <code>CONN</code>) before authentication. A separate test confirmed the port was reachable, narrowing the issue to the local Node/Nodemailer connection. To protect the project scope and timeline, further debugging was deferred. Therefore, no claim of successful email notification is made.</p>

<h2>9. Student Reflection</h2>

<p><strong>Student revision required:</strong> This section must be rewritten in your own words before submission. Do not submit the prompts below as if they are your personal reflection.</p>

<p>Before this project, describe your real starting point. For example, explain only the JavaScript, REST API, MongoDB, Shopify, or database skills that you genuinely had before beginning. Then explain the new learning that you can support with your project evidence.</p>

<p>One important learning area was data modelling. The prototype required a distinction between a customer <code>NotificationRequest</code>, an incoming <code>ProcessedInventoryEvent</code>, a unique delivery ID, a request status, and an external inventory reference. Another learning area was reliability: the duplicate-event test showed why idempotency is important, because a repeated event must not repeat a state-changing action.</p>

<p>Reflect honestly on the actual challenges. The evidence log records a Mongoose index conflict and an initial matching problem caused by a non-matching inventory item ID. Also explain what you learned about scope management when the Ethereal SMTP connection failed. The ethical response was to record the limitation, not to claim success or spend unlimited time debugging an external integration.</p>

<h2>10. Future Improvements</h2>

<p>The current MVP has clear limitations that define future work:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Email Verification:</strong> The local SMTP socket issue needs to be resolved to capture proof of email generation.</li>
    <li><strong>Live Webhooks:</strong> The project used a controlled test fixture. Future work should register a real Shopify webhook and verify its HMAC signature to prove live integration.</li>
    <li><strong>Reconciliation:</strong> Because Shopify (n.d.)<a href="#ref-3">[3]</a> explains that webhook delivery is not guaranteed, a production system would need a scheduled job to reconcile pending requests against actual Shopify inventory.</li>
    <li><strong>Production Security:</strong> This development prototype uses invented data. A real app would need formal privacy reviews, rate limiting, and secure secret management.</li>
</ul>

<p>This prototype makes the core event-processing, data, and reliability decisions visible. It provides a bounded foundation for future development, while keeping unfinished email delivery and live webhook behaviour clearly identified as future work.</p>

